CRITICAL — Action-repetition trap detection (check BEFORE planning):
Before choosing any action, review Recent execution feedback and the last 3 actions. If ANY of these patterns is present, you MUST break the loop:
• MENU LOOP: If menu(option="open") appeared 2+ times in a row, the menu is likely already open. Use choose_item(), choose_option(), or menu(option="close") instead of opening it again.
• INTERACT SPAM: If interact(direction="X") returned "no confirmation" 2+ times in a row, that target does NOT respond to interact(). Try move() onto the target tile, a different direction, or a completely different approach.
• TOOL SPAM: Only trigger this trap if use(direction="X") ran 3+ times AND task progress quantity did NOT increase during that streak. Stardew's use() returns "no confirmation" even on successful swings, so repeated use in the same direction is legitimate for chain-clearing (scythe/pickaxe/axe). Trust task progress quantity as the ground truth, not "no confirmation" messages.
• MOVE BLOCKED: If move() on the same axis failed 2+ times, sidestep 1-2 tiles on the perpendicular axis before retrying. Drop magnitude to 1 tile.
• OSCILLATION: If recent moves alternate between opposite directions (e.g. left then right, up then down) for 3+ steps, you are stuck in place. Commit to ONE direction and keep moving until blocked or you reach a new area, then try a perpendicular direction.

Current-state priority rules:
0. TASK LOCK: Your actions must serve the "Current task" shown above. If the task is go_to_bed, every action must advance toward entering the farmhouse and reaching the bed — even if you see debris, crops, or NPCs nearby. If the task is go_to_coop, every action must navigate toward the coop. Never take actions for a different task domain just because the environment shows tempting targets.
1. You MUST ground your plan in the current game information shown above, especially Current Menu, Location, Current position, Current facing direction, Current tool and interaction effect point, Item in your hand, Surroundings, Toolbar information, and the latest screenshot.
2. If the current game information conflicts with Summarization of recent history, the last action reasoning, self-reflection, or an older subtask assumption, you MUST trust the current game information. EXCEPTION: this rule never overrides rule 0 — visible debris/crops/NPCs do not change the task domain.
3. Do not assume a target, obstacle, menu state, tool state, or reachable interaction opportunity unless it is supported by the current game information.
3a. Treat any missing or omitted Surroundings coordinate as unknown, not empty, traversable, tillable, or interactable. Never justify a move, use(), or interact() by saying a direction is "probably empty" just because it is not listed.
4. Every planned action must be explainable by a concrete fact from the current environment. Avoid plans that only follow stale history or a generic task pattern.
5. If a Long-term memory reference appears, use it only as same-task historical success context. If the current facts show an adjacent/reachable target, blocker, exit, building, or better waypoint, follow the current facts. Otherwise prefer the memory route prefix over a generic search/probe move.
6. If the latest execution feedback or failure signals say the player is in the wrong position, not adjacent, too far away, standing on the porch, or has repeated zero-progress productive actions, then Step 1 should usually be move(...). Even if the current facts show a clearable obstacle directly in front of the player or on the current effect point, prefer a grounded reroute first unless rerouting is not grounded.
6a. If Front tile summary identifies a concrete building or obstacle directly ahead, treat it as a grounded blocker. Do not begin by repeating the same blocked-direction move, use(), or interact() unless the plan first routes around it or has a concrete reason that clearing is now necessary.
6b. If Blocked recovery hint names a clearable obstacle and matching tool, treat that as a fallback, not the default. Prefer a grounded reroute, nearby waypoint, or different axis order before switching tools to clear.
6c. If the blocker is not clearly removable from the current tile, Step 1 should change route or local alignment instead of repeating the same-axis probe.
6d. Prefer Current blocker signature and Nearest grounded target summary over ambiguous image prose when picking the next waypoint or interaction target.

